These are lessons we should have learned from the 50‚Äôs that was really brought home in @RebeccaSkloot's story of the #hela cell line. Have we already forgotten? (8/8)
Even as scientists think of new restrictions on the use #CRISPR in human embryos, it‚Äôs still worth asking, whose cells? what circumstances? who will actually benefit? who absorbs the risk? (7/8)
‚Ä¶ and this use of #CRISPR has the potential to reduce funding for far more effective harm reduction practices that actively benefit marginalized populations (6/8)
Worse, the #CRISPR technology used in this way is impossible to scale (expensive, impractical) and does nothing for people currently living with HIV AIDS (5/8)
Did they think that gene-editing was the only solution if they wanted healthy babies? Were the risks properly explained to them? Could the parents even make an informed choice? (4/8)

But, in the #CRISPRbabies study, only one parent (the father) had HIV, HIV+ moms appeared to be not be part of the study. Did the parents know that existing treatment would reduce the risk of transmission to practically zero? (3/8)

Others have already commented on how the downstream effects of the CCR5 knockout are unknown and thus the children may be at greater risk for other adverse outcomes even if they are at decreased risk of HIV (not yet proven) (2/8)

I want to boost the signal in the #CRISPRbabies discussion about how marginalized populations take on the brunt of risk in scientific experimentation even though they are unlikely to be the beneficiaries of the final technology (1/8)

Because of the history of the Homo sapiens populations, we are all descendants from Africa, somewhere near the African Great Lakes (Lake Victoria, etc.) https://t.co/9OCx3zm2K1

The paper about the extra 100Mb found by sequencing ancestral tribes in Africa is another deep dive into finding variation that goes deeper than the 1000 Genomes project managed to go since it is now orders of magnitude cheaper to do the same level of @illumina sequencing.

In the same way that it took people 1 year, sometimes 2-5 years to adopt GRCh38 and switch to it from GRCh37, it will take time for people to adopt graph-based reference genomes and all the associated tools

But this graph-based reference genome, and the associated tools that are needed to use it for alignment are not being widely adopted yet. The basic tools are there, but it takes time for the tools to be adopted by other tools developers.
From then on, the idea of building a graph reference genome came to the fore: represent the human reference as a graph with multiple paths rather than a flat sequence of chromosomes

The 1000 Genomes project was set up to cover most original populations on Earth, this is, populations containing most of the ancestral alleles, both in Single Nucleotide changes (SNP) and Insertions and Deletions (indels) and structural variants (SVs and CNVs)

This doesn't make the ethical decisions about when (if ever) to do germline editing any easier - it just gives a framework to make that decision which has the support of society.

When asked by journalists yesterday I continued to point out that (a) strong regulation in UK, Europe and US exists (I think the UK's is particular well designed) and (b) it can accommodate developments such as CRISPR

This is no theoretical concept - the more technically complex procedure of mitochondrial donation, with as complex ethical questions ("three parent babies" was the unfortunate headline sometimes) was responsibly handled and licensed.

I am like a broken record about this, but the HFEA in the UK is an excellent example of good regulation. It can appropriately allow research; it thinks hard about applications and has a process that gets input across society to license techniques.

For genomic scientists - the important thing is not whether germline/embryo CRISPR could be useful now or in the future - it is how we do the research and assessment of this technology in a way that has the trust of society

Our review thus aims to bridge these various approaches to study how perturbed stability can cause disease, and how they can be used to develop predictive models and what they can be used for. Comments are welcome.
When disease is caused by loss of stability it may be possible to rescue function by restabilizing the protein or by perturbing the protein quality control system https://t.co/v0JDFS1FbI

We would like to be able to predict these effects from structure or sequence to aid in diagnosis and develop mechanistic models. We focus on biophysical models of stability, statistical models of sequences and a model trained on DMS data https://t.co/dEfaCoVO9b

Deep mutational scanning (DMS) experiments provide data for variant effects on protein function and abundance, that can be used to train or validate models. DMS provides information on the effect of a broad range of missense mutations. https://t.co/DCieA79CKA

We aim to link studies of how mutations may cause genetic diseases via decreased protein stability. Perturbed thermodynamic or kinetic stability can lead to an increase of locally or globally unfolded proteins, that may in turn be recognized by the protein quality control system https://t.co/Ko1mj7PNlh

For my European colleagues - the UK has only gone slightly mad - it happens to every country and person occassionally; hopefully our schizophrenia will heal and whether it is 2nd referendum, or this deal, please remain friends, collaborate, discuss and be good neighbours :)

I can only imagine a no-deal Brexit in the context of a referendum with this as an option. Everything I've heard and read says it is unimaginably risky and perverse to inflict almost certain disruption - including many avoidable deaths.

In that is host of details (visa policy for skilled scientists, technicians, students) and I appreciate a host of details away from my field. Such is the world, and this is what good government is about.

I want the UK to be- open, liberal, appropriately regulated (quite a balancing act), broadly fair. I want science+technology to flourish, I want us to take a responsible role in the world, I want us to be a good neighbour to our European colleagues - we cannot change geography!

BUT: Quite possibly May's deal - some tweaks - will go through. As messy and as wrong as it is, if Parliament - representative democracy - votes for it, then I think people like myself *must* move on; out of the EU, what country do we want to be?
(And any "Remain" campaign has to be more effective and really think about campaigning and not virtue signalling etc).And I hope we vote to stay in the EU if this comes about.

It's going to be important to frame any possible 2nd referendum not as "you were wrong, we were right" but that "these are the practical, worked out options of what Brexit means; in the balance of things important to you, do you really want this?". The answer can validly be yes.

I genuinely think we were in the best place 2 years ago - in the EU but out of the Euro. I argued this then and if we have a 2nd referendum I will argue it again. But note many Leave voters were *not* racists/bigots but had a variety of other reasons

Moving on - we've got at least another 2 years though of this dominating UK politics, if not longer (the comparisons to the 1921 Anglo Irish agreement and the two parties on the right in Ireland are fascinating). So - deep breath - we're best case half way.

I felt dirty and ashamed of my government when they said this; they should have apologised in my view though this is sadly not their highest priority. I - and  many many other Brits - really appreciate the people from the EU who have moved and made the UK far better. Thank you.

It's at best embarrassing to use this rhetoric; at worst it reflects of a true streak of nasty them-and-us thinking. the "citizen's of nowhere" rhetoric places Brits like me in a similar disdain, but this comment hurts more.

They've worked, settled, participated in society, (yes, paid their taxes) and enriched the institutions, companies, communities and nation they are in. It's a two-way street, and they did not queue to come nor are they grateful just for the opportunity to be in the UK.

First thing to say was there was yet another flash of the bad, myopic rhetoric around "queue jumpers" that completely misunderstand that the vast majority of people from the EU living and working in the UK came, freely (and legally of course), for mutual benefit.
It is hard to quite judge where we will end up - probability of May's deal seems on the rise; I find it hard to believe a no-deal Brexit is realistic; a 2nd referendum is an appreciable possibility.

As I finally leave from Heidelberg back home (it's been 4 European days away) I - like many Brits and people in the UK - are watching in sort of somewhat queasy fascination the outcome of this stage of Brexit

In this @NatureComms article We propose two divergent modes of tumor evolution A) ‚ÄòCamouflage‚Äô Cells with poised chromatin utilise 'stem-cell switch' to undergo transdifferentiation; B) ‚ÄòDesignated Survivor‚Äô Pre-existing drug-resistant populations leads to Darwinian selection. https://t.co/RahZQDeKDt

Finally we employed RNAi and small molecule screens and identified BRD4 as a key molecule for drug-induced cellular plasticity, importantly JQ1 (BRD4-inhibitor) could reverse the cisplatin resistance in these cells. https://t.co/5pxJLuxz1Y

We wanted to test if cellular plasticity is linked with rewiring of chromatin landscape and we were surprised to observe that genes associated with cellular plasticity were already decorated with H3K3me3 marks. These promoters gained H3K27ac & lost H3K27me3 during tumor evolution https://t.co/1z54p20snN

In a phenotypic screen for ~2000 TF‚Äôs we identified Sox9 as the key master regulator of cellular plasticity. Further experiments indicated 'Sox2 to Sox9' stem-cell switch during drug-resistance. We validated this observation in larger patient cohorts including TCGA datasets. https://t.co/xYvuDSQxi9

Interestingly we observed loss of Sox2 during cellular plasticity (and mesenchymal phenotype) but gain of Sox2 during Darwinian selection and epithelial properties. We validated these observations by both computational and experimental observations. https://t.co/v4I568YlIb

Since two different epithelial cells took divergent paths for drug-resistance we sought to identify cell of origin in these tumors. Epithelial cells displayed higher heterogeneity in terms of stem potential and expressed SOX2 a bonafide oncogene in SCC. https://t.co/0Zjb6ESGFV

In our quest to identify drug-resistant cells we stumbled across cellular plasticity, as we observed drug-induced transcriptional shift from Epithelial to Mesenchymal fate. In case of Darwinian selection, we identified drug-resistant ‚ÄòEpithelial‚Äô cells. https://t.co/EV4Zzu8tVB

We performed single cell RNA-seq to identify if ‚Äòrare‚Äô drug-resistant cells are involved in this process. We profiled ~1300 single cells from different time points of tumor evolution, i.e. na√Øve, resistant, drug-holiday and metastatic. https://t.co/KioI6FAXaM

We employed patient-derived primary cells to model drug-resistance and were surprised to observe two very distinct (selection & adaptation) modes of tumor evolution in HNSCC. we validated these observations in Pdx models and same patient (before/after cisplatin treatment) tumors. https://t.co/cIbWGKGAQo

Ever wondered why chemotherapy works for some patients but not for others? Well, we did, and discovered that tumors evolve differently under the selection pressure of same drug and ‚Äòfate‚Äô lies in the ‚Äòfidelity of stem-cell hierarchy‚Äô. https://t.co/bWal2VerHU

Ultimately a 2nd referendum is likely to be a closer run thing than many Remain supporters realise. The "Leave" vote was a coalition between people who did not like the democratic deficit + other fudges of EU and people who disliked what the UK had become over the last 20 years
and finally (c) that there has always been a fair whack of immigration from outside of the EU which has gotten completely and stupidly mixed up with parts of this debate.

I'd note that (a) the UK economy - like many others - needs a healthy number of talented, motivated people from other countries (b) these immigrants are a massive economic boost (pay taxes etc) though ascertainment to the negative side of immigration in media is all too easy
The question is whether control in particular of movement of people is more important symbolically than serious influence over the major trading rules with our largest partner

(a) UK politicians need to basically be at impasse (quite likely), (b) EU nation states and EU commission need to fudge leaving (some sort of purgatory) and have the largess to allow UK to vote in on old terms (big ask) (c) then there is a real question to the UK populace

Given that this week we (UK) will actually know what "leaving Europe" means (plus "taking back control" etc), I really think it would be right to re-do the referendum. I don't imagine this is easy ...

Sometimes you need to go younger to get the right mix of expertise and gender - don't worry about that in my opinion - this exposes clever people to the next level up and helps retain female talent in the field in general.

Other things (a) senior women get asked to do a lot, plus they often have more complex home commitments, so don't be surprised by a polite no (my rule of thumb - you need to invite 1.5x) (b) in biology (inc bioinformatics) there are easily enough good women - just takes effort

Top tip; having researchers come to mind because you need to achieve some level of gender balance - this is a good thing. Putting in the invitation to panel etc that it is "to achieve gender balance" is really not good (duh!) and *NOT THE POINT* of gender balance.

We are one big #HPC family, regardless of affiliation, working in one *the* coolest professions on this planet. Using big computers and small, we‚Äôre all trying to contribute something to this field. And including people from all walks of life  makes HPC better. #hpcinspires #SC18

So now I ponder how my latest affiliation will be received at #SC18 and reflect on my experience since SC09. So if you‚Äôre attending SC, especially if you carry one of those prestigious badges, consider making time to meet those who approach you, and ignore their affiliations.

So from then on I made a point to ignore badges at any conference I attended, ask people their name instead of reading, and treat them as individuals. I made a ton of great friends this way (obviously the badge affiliation continued to help) and also great collaborations #SC18

Fast forward to 2012 and I joined @ORNL (thanks to a chance meeting at SC btw!) and my SC experience became drastically different. People would look down at my badge, notice the affiliation, and stay to chat! It felt weird because nothing had changed about me, just my job. #SC18

I knew just a handful of people from help forums, #HPCtwitter wasn‚Äôt much of a thing yet. I finally met in person @DoctorFortran at the @intel booth and @hpcgal at the #WHPC BoF. But for the most part, when I went to talk with speakers, they‚Äôd look down my badge and ignore me üòû

It's up to us to decide what to do with that knowledge, and whether we will choose to value one another.üå†
In the end, everything in our lives is biology. In the same way everything in our lives is chemistry, or physics. We are made of stuff. That stuff has properties. Scientists study stuff.
It is incurious. It conceives of knowledge only in terms of its uses.
It is righteous. It tells us what it is ok to think. It suggests we are immoral if we want to know how we came to be ourselves.
It contradicts itself. It suggests biology is at once inept, unable to predict anything, and also too powerful to unleash.

It argues that a biology of sex, gender & orientation is "dangerous" and "can be exploited." That is true in exactly the same way a fork, a hammer, or algebra might be dangerous. Anything worth knowing has the ability to be put to use, sometimes malevolently.

That‚Äôs research performed with public funds. That‚Äôs your tax dollars going to waste. That‚Äôs animals that didn‚Äôt need to be bred, housed, fed, drugged, or sacrificed. That‚Äôs time and money that could‚Äôve been invested towards new discoveries and training researchers.

Of course, it is not the researchers fault here either. #Reproducibility is a huge and serious problem. We need to make sure results can be replicated or they‚Äôre pointless theatrics. Anyone knowingly spreading fabricated results has blood on their hands and is wasting our time.

As researchers, we can be desensitised and complacent about the costs of our research. It‚Äôs important to make sure we use as few animals as possible yet also enough that the data doesn‚Äôt go to waste either. We have a responsibility to get the most out of data that costs lives.

Every year, my colleagues at @RIKEN_IMS hold a memorial ceremony for the animals‚Äîincluding thousands of mice‚Äîsacrificed in our experiments. Another exercise was to explain your research project to your neighbour within 2 minutes, then in 1 minute, then in 30 seconds, and finally in 15 seconds. With the goal being to successively distill the essence of your research. And to realise not every aspect can be crammed in

In non genetics terms ; our genetics is far, far more fluid and interwoven than our classification of people into ‚Äúrace‚Äù, ‚Äúethnic groups‚Äù, despite the strong self identification and classification people have.
This constant historical moving and mixing means almost every allele is present in nearly every location you find (enough) humans - frequencies drift around but we constantly mixing

This movement is in the context of surprisingly *undiverse* genetic variation of humans - we are less diverse than chimps and the vast majority of alleles are from our common, founding, East African source
The Americas are a different matter, though the extremely violent and thorough mixing post Columbus means in terms of genetic diversity *now* it is very high
Plenty of trade and movement of people down the East African coast and along the Nile. Plenty of movement across Eurasia as this Monogol <=> Finn study shows
In Eurasia + Africa there is plenty of evidence of gene flow throughout history; the Sahara was somewhat of barrier but by no means complete
People‚Äôs intuition about human movements is strangly skewed that this only happened trans-continentally 16 cent onwards due to ship based trading. This is not true

The counterargument from @nanopore @Clive_G_Brown would be: don't tie yourself down to a $1/3M Sequel machine, instead buy $1000 MinIONs (and flowcells) on a per-project needs basis
Some will say that an @illumina Sequel gives more certainty to customers of the technology not being at risk of discontinuation from @PacBio fizzling out (like Helicos and others)
There are plenty of examples of projects that were already run on short+long reads combo. Where short was usually @illumina and long was either @pacbio or @nanopore

This is all very hypothetical at this stage, but I've been thinking about it consistently for long enough that it might come to be at some point.
I'd also probably sell, "breeder's mixes" of segregating seeds from early generations after a cross, so others can get involved in #plantbreeding more easily.

I'd only sell seeds I'd grown myself, so this will limit the potential scale of the venture.I would have to make more efforts to isolate existing varieties against cross-pollination than I currently do.

If a variety was originally bred by a company, govt agency, or other professional entity... (Some varieties have been in circulation so long that the originator deserves recognition, but perhaps not a percentage of the cash.) I'm still working out exactly what to do in this case.

If a variety was simply passed along or traded to me, the last person in the chain wouldn't get a percentage. If I could track down the original breeder, then that individual would get a percentage. ("Green Zebra" tomato, for instance.)

To help encourage the freelance #plantbreeding community, I've been thinking of implementing a royalty system.If a variety was bred by someone else, they'd get a certain percentage of any $. If a wild variety was collected by someone else, they would get a smaller percentage.

I've been thinking about opening a [very small] seed selling website to sell varieties I've bred. I know it is unlikely to ever have enough of an income stream to by my main income. It would be a side project, but wouldn't be too much more ongoing work than I'm already doing.

That said, I‚Äôm not touching any of these substances while I‚Äôm in Japan. Nothing is worth risking deportation. When you are abroad, follow the laws of the country you‚Äôre in. Seriously, be careful. Stories of international students being caught with drugs are common here.

I‚Äôm not suggesting that every country will change drug laws overnight. I‚Äôm looking forward to the new insights that will come from th places that di. We need understanding and evidence to drive medical decisions with lives and wellbeing are at stake, not fear and paranoia.

Yet illegal substances are off-the-table for most researchers.  A lot of research is done on public funds. The govt doesn‚Äôt just decide what we can do legally and ethically, it decides what we get funds to do. We cannot find out the potential benefits without no funds to do it.

What could be gained by regulating the market and making sure that the products available are as safe and pure and affordable as possible? What benefits could we get by giving it to patients that need it? We‚Äôll never know if we can‚Äôt investigate these matters.

Would it really cost more for governments to regulate them than what they currently spend enforcing drug laws and maintaining prisons? Is it worth treating the victims of poverty and addiction as criminals to ruin their careers? Is it safe to take drugs at home without a doctor?

We banned alcohol and we all know that turned out. No one stopped drinking and the black market thrived. We all know that didn‚Äôt work and the decision to ban it in the first place was political, not rational. So why do we assume it‚Äôs an exception and it‚Äôs case closed on others?

These are not the decisions of rational mind, they‚Äôre the driven by the public opinion and the politics of another time. It‚Äôs an arbitrary list of substances that people need ‚Äúunderstand the risks‚Äù and ‚Äúuse in moderation‚Äù. Others are banned but we all know people still use them.

Heroin is a serious illegal narcotic and yet you can find Morphine (a controlled substance) in almost any hospital in the world. Illegal drugs are not necessarily more harmful, they‚Äôre more poorly understood. No one has examined the effects of marijuana as thoroughly as tobacco.

Why is it that consuming alcohol which destroys lives is totally acceptable? Tobacco is legal despite the well documented health risks associated with it. Caffeine is an ubiquitous part of our lives and it‚Äôs a highly addictive mind altering substance.

Let‚Äôs understand the potential harms and take away stigma. Let‚Äôs treat addiction as a health crisis like any other, instead of hiding it under red tape. Let‚Äôs treat drugs like medications that need to be understood, not to be feared.

This isn‚Äôt just, let‚Äôs see if my favourite drug kills cancer cells in a Petri dish (it probably will in high doses but also kill your healthy cells). This is let‚Äôs see what the active ingredients are and what they do. We can do better than excluding some substances from science.

An often overlooked benefit to regulating rather than banning drugs (never mind the tax revenue) are that researchers can continue working on it. Medical use does not only mean treatments, it can also be testing of new medical applications and research.https://t.co/L1zyHdqsr9

Record neural activity optically using gcamp while touching neurons in periphery. Piezo2 knock-outs eliminate soft-touch responses in trigeminal ganglion.
Patients missing Piezo2 lose gliding touch in glabrous skin but not hairy skin. Hairy skin contains c-tactile afferents -- caress responsive neurons. Suggests it is not important in caress responses.

Pseudoathetosis is a set of writhing movements associated with a profound loss of proprioception. Patients with mutation in Piezo2 may exhibit pseudoathetosis. Require orders of magnitude more force to detect touch.
Piezo2 is a stretch-gated ion channel to sense deformation of cell membrane -- modulates many sensory responses to touch.

These tree sequences aren't just an efficient storage format for data, they are rich in biological signal. Here's another beautiful figure from @pkalbers showing population structure in SGDP and 1000G at the global, population and individual scale. https://t.co/svRp2KlSVs

We applied tsinfer to large scale human datasets (1000G, SGDP and UK Biobank). We can infer these tree sequences pretty quickly. E.g. after extracting the data (kicking and screaming) from VCF, inference takes only 5 minutes for SGDP on a decent server!

Our method (tsinfer) infers tree sequences from real data. It uses the amazing computational properties of tree sequences to scale to datasets of unprecedented size. The key technical advance is a tree sequence based implementation of the Li and Stephens model, which is *fast*.

Tree sequences can potentially store population scale variation data in a fraction of the space required by present-day formats. This illustration from @pkalbers shows how we could store 5 billion simulated human chromosomes in ~1TiB. https://t.co/6hbB9joFH4

The "succinct tree sequence" is a new data structure to represent such ancestry. Similar to---but distinct from---ARGs. Tree sequences grew out of coalescent sims (msprime), and can now also be used in forward simulations:  https://t.co/JAoJ1bmYA5

Inferring ancestry with recombination (aka ARGs) has been a goal in popgen for decades, but computational cost has severely limited practical applications. Mundane issues like the lack of a standard interchange format also limit adoption.
